WEBVTT

00:02.478 --> 00:23.552
March 10, 1999, sitting in the living room with Jim 
Cashion, getting ready to hear his recollections

00:02.478 --> 00:23.552
of life at A&M, both when he was growing up, but also 
as a student.

00:23.572 --> 00:28.840
Your parents came to A&M when?

00:29.157 --> 00:33.060
I believe in August of 1926. Let's go back and tell 
me a little about them and their experience before

00:33.781 --> 00:38.625
coming here. Okay, well, my dad graduated from 
Erskine College in South Carolina and came to

00:39.546 --> 00:58.523
Austin College, I'm not sure if it was his first 
job, about 1912.

01:00.258 --> 01:07.168
I have his, an Austin College ring

01:00.258 --> 01:07.168
in 1912. And he was secretary of the YMCA and at one 
point athletic director at Austin College until

01:07.248 --> 01:22.790
World War I. And went into the service

01:30.430 --> 01:41.272
I guess under the auspices of the YMCA, I really 
don't know for sure, but I think it's sort of like

01:30.430 --> 01:41.272
the USO was in World War II. But he was in France with 
the YMCA during World War I, and after the war he He

01:51.203 --> 02:02.220
joined the British YMCA and was in Egypt and Africa 
for a little

01:51.203 --> 02:02.220
over a year. My mother was a native of Wills Point, 
Texas. And she had friends who lived in Sherman.

02:13.077 --> 02:17.143
And through that connection met my dad just before 
World War II, World War I, and they

02:17.866 --> 02:35.129
were married in 1925, I believe, 24 or 25, I'm not 
exactly sure, after he came back to Austin College

02:17.866 --> 02:35.129
after the war. After the war? After World War I. Was 
he again with the YMCA there at Austin College?

02:42.619 --> 02:45.122
That's when he was athletic director. Did he have 
any other duties other than that? I don't think so.

02:50.091 --> 02:56.037
I know he was the general secretary of the YMCA. As 
you understand it, in today's terminology, what

02:56.057 --> 03:07.287
services did the YMCA provide at that era on a 
campus? Well, you're talking about at A&M? No, at

03:10.069 --> 03:10.609
Austin College. I'm not sure about Austin 
College. I'm assuming that it was more or less like

03:14.330 --> 03:23.403
the YMCA program at A&M was after he came down here. 
All right. And they come down here in 20... He came

03:26.187 --> 03:27.529
down here in 1925. He came down as the general 
secretary of YMCA. Do you know who it was that hired

03:31.174 --> 03:32.836
him? Do you know any of the circumstances that... 
No. You don't remember what his pay was or anything

03:35.740 --> 03:38.204
like that? No. I remember one time... Well,

03:42.190 --> 03:52.982
this was just before World War II. And I guess I was 
probably in high school because I was interested

03:53.002 --> 03:59.650
in his buying a new car. And I went with him one day to 
pick up his paycheck at the fiscal office. It was in

04:08.240 --> 04:10.763
the new administration building. And he couldn't 
find a parking place, and so he just double parked

04:11.502 --> 04:17.370
and told me to run in and get his check. And I did, and 
I looked at it, and I think it was about maybe $300.

04:21.675 --> 04:26.602
And I thought, oh, my goodness, anybody that's 
making that much money ought to be able to buy a car.

04:26.862 --> 04:28.064
This was his monthly check. This was his monthly 
check. All right. So I imagine his salary is $3,500

04:31.729 --> 04:35.393
or so. I'm not sure. All right. He came, and the Y 
building... that we know today. And as far as you

04:41.239 --> 04:50.067
know, as far as you can describe what the building 
contained at the time he got here. Well, the YMCA

04:50.087 --> 04:57.914
building at that time was the nearest thing A&M had 
to a student center.

05:00.317 --> 05:09.505
They had a semi-basement, but on the main floor 
there was a big lobby. They had ping pong tables.

05:12.508 --> 05:15.813
They had easy chairs. They subscribed to nearly 
all the major newspapers in the state that the

05:15.873 --> 05:24.025
students could read. They had a desk in the lobby 
there that the students could buy postcards and

05:24.045 --> 05:34.481
stamps and stationery.

05:36.924 --> 05:38.867
And behind the lobby there was a chapel. and the 
chapel was used for all sorts of meetings, but the

05:39.910 --> 05:55.226
main group that met there, as I recall, was the 
first president of the church, or the eight

05:39.910 --> 05:55.226
emperors that met in the chapel of YMCA. On Sunday 
at normal worship hour, I am expressing a bit of

05:55.646 --> 06:08.820
surprise that any specific denomination could 
have used it Every Sunday? Every Sunday. And there

06:12.214 --> 06:22.948
was a

06:12.214 --> 06:22.948
union Sunday school made up of several 
denominations that met in the old assembly hall

06:12.214 --> 06:22.948
every Sunday morning. Who taught that? Was there 
any legendary teacher? My dad was taught for a

06:27.534 --> 06:30.137
while. Caroline Mitchell was one of the teachers.

06:36.345 --> 06:38.368
I can't really remember...

06:40.120 --> 06:48.493
And we met under the stage

06:40.120 --> 06:48.493
in the assembly hall. And then later, we met under 
the stage in Guyon Hall. There was a space. You're

06:56.545 --> 06:57.386
saying we. Did you go before you were an A&M 
student? Oh, yeah. By the time I was an A&M student,

07:02.313 --> 07:07.601
the Union Sunday School was defunct. Oh, OK. 
Probably in elementary school. They gave you a pen

07:15.071 --> 07:17.794
if you attended for a year. The second year, you got 
a wreath around the pen. And from then on, you got a

07:22.139 --> 07:24.582
bar for each year. I think I had six or eight bars. 
The record was held by a guy named Duke Thornton,

07:29.046 --> 07:39.017
who is currently a member of South Minister 
Presbyterian Church in Sugar Land. And I think he

07:39.250 --> 07:44.897
had 14 bars.

